AGI - Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan > moves away from the protests inflamed the country in the last week, discusses on the phone with Russian colleague Vladimir Putin > and in the meantime cultivates relations with Africa with a visit to Guinea. In spite of the country split in two after the arrest of the mayor of Istanbul<a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-03-28/turchia-arrestato-anche- lawyer-di-imamoglu-30641611/"> Ekrem Imamoglu</a>, Erdogan reiterated to Putin the availability of Turkey > to host a negotiation that ends
The Turkish president at first seemed to have distanced himself from the investigation that struck Imamoglu, then began to criticize the opposition, re-carnating the charges of corruption and defining "vandali and terrorists" those who clashed with the police. Interventions that have raised tension in the country. With the end of Ramadan> party approaching Erdogan made his move announcing 9 days of holiday. Days in which, traditionally, cities are emptied with people leaving to their places of origin, locations abroad or the south coast of the country. Nine days with which Erdogan will try to calm the souls and the waters, but that could not be enough, also because Imamoglu is in prison and the protest could start again.
<div </div
In the last few days the demonstrations have been flattered and there have been no clashes. However, the opposition organized a large demonstration on Saturday in Istanbul, not in front of the municipality but in the Maltepe district. Erdogan preferred to go to Africa, where Turkey has great interests, but above all to talk to Putin about the latest developments in the conflict in Ukraine and Syria. With him he reiterated that Turkey is at the forefront and ready to organize a negotiation for peace in Ukraine. A strategy with which Erdogan takes from distances from internal polemics, from protests, but also raises the role of Turkey within the international community.
The same international community that has criticized him harshly in recent days. One way to reiterate that in Turkey the work of the judiciary is to be respected, as independent, to the point that even a delicate investigation like this can go on alone and he can continue his work as a great mediator. &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
